{:proof/updated-at "2026-03-29T21:17:25.410134826Z", :proof/falsify-completed? true, :proof/cycles [{:cycle/id "apm-a01A04-C001", :cycle/blocker-id "root", :cycle/phase :completed, :cycle/phases-completed [:observe :propose :execute :validate :classify :integrate :commit :gate-review], :cycle/phase-data {:observe {:blocker-id "root", :notes "WHAT IS REALLY BEING ASKED: Three parts about the volume of the unit ball B_{n,1} in R^n. Part (a) asks for a recurrence: express vol(B_{n+1}) in terms of vol(B_n) via an integral against [f(t)]^n for some f: R -> [0,1]. Part (b) says the integral factor goes to zero. Part (c) concludes A^n vol(B_n) -> 0 for any A > 0: ball volume decays faster than any exponential. The underlying phenomenon is that high-dimensional unit balls have vanishing volume — almost all the volume of the unit cube lies in the corners.\n\nWHY IT IS HARD: Part (a) requires the Cavalieri slicing trick: cut B_{n+1} perpendicular to one axis. The cross-section at height t is an n-ball of radius sqrt(1-t^2). Students who have not seen this before will not find f(t) under exam pressure. Part (b) is a clean DCT application once you notice f(t) < 1 for all t except t=0. Part (c) is a telescoping product argument: if the ratio of consecutive volumes goes to 0, you can make each ratio smaller than 1/A eventually, forcing super-exponential decay. Students who try explicit Gamma function formulas are taking the hard road — the exam tests Fubini + DCT, not special functions."}, :propose {:approach "Cavalieri slicing for (a), DCT for (b), telescoping ratio bound for (c).", :notes "THE KEY INSIGHT: Slice B_{n+1} at height x_{n+1} = t. The slice is B_{n,sqrt(1-t^2)}. By Fubini: vol(B_{n+1}) = integral vol(slice) dt = vol(B_n) * integral [sqrt(1-t^2)]^n dt. So f(t) = sqrt(1-t^2) on [-1,1], zero elsewhere.\n\nTHE NAIVE APPROACH THAT FAILS: Compute vol(B_n) = pi^{n/2}/Gamma(n/2+1) explicitly via the Gamma function and use Stirling's approximation. This works for part (c) but requires careful asymptotic analysis that is harder than the Fubini/DCT approach, and it completely misses the structural insight of the recurrence. The exam rewards the slicing approach because it uses tools from the measure theory syllabus (Fubini, DCT, scaling)."}, :execute {:artifacts ["proof-a01A04-v2"], :notes "THE CLEAN PROOF:\n\nPart (a). Define f: R -> [0,1] by f(t) = sqrt(1-t^2) for |t| <= 1 and f(t) = 0 otherwise.\n\nSlice B_{n+1,1} perpendicular to the (n+1)-th axis at height t. A point (x_1,...,x_{n+1}) is in B_{n+1,1} iff x_1^2+...+x_{n+1}^2 <= 1. At fixed x_{n+1} = t, this requires x_1^2+...+x_n^2 <= 1-t^2, which describes the n-ball of radius sqrt(1-t^2) (existing only for |t| <= 1).\n\nBy Fubini:\n  m(B_{n+1,1}) = integral_{-1}^{1} m(B_{n,sqrt(1-t^2)}) dt\n\nLebesgue measure scales as r^n in dimension n: m(B_{n,r}) = r^n m(B_{n,1}). So:\n  m(B_{n+1,1}) = integral_{-1}^{1} (1-t^2)^{n/2} m(B_{n,1}) dt = m(B_{n,1}) integral [f(t)]^n dt\n\nsince f(t)=0 outside [-1,1] extends the integral to all of R. QED (a).\n\nPart (b). Show integral [f(t)]^n dt -> 0. Note f(t) in [0,1] everywhere, and f(t) < 1 for all t != 0 (since 1-t^2 < 1). At t=0, f(0)=1. So [f(t)]^n -> 0 for all t != 0 (powers of a number in [0,1) go to zero), and [f(0)]^n = 1 for all n. Since {0} has measure zero, [f(t)]^n -> 0 a.e. The dominator |[f(t)]^n| <= chi_{[-1,1]}(t) is integrable. By DCT: integral [f(t)]^n dt -> 0. QED (b).\n\nPart (c). Fix A > 0. Let r_n = m(B_{n+1,1})/m(B_{n,1}) = integral [f(t)]^n dt. By (b), r_n -> 0. Choose N so that r_n < 1/(2A) for all n >= N. Then for n > N:\n  m(B_{n,1}) = m(B_{N,1}) * product_{k=N}^{n-1} r_k <= m(B_{N,1}) * (1/(2A))^{n-N}\n\nSo: A^n m(B_{n,1}) <= m(B_{N,1}) * (2A)^N * (1/2)^n -> 0 since (1/2)^n -> 0. QED (c)."}, :validate {:validation-artifacts ["lean-proofs/a01A04/Main.lean"], :notes "NON-CIRCULARITY ANALYSIS: The proof composes four independent facts: (i) Fubini/Cavalieri slicing — general measure theory; (ii) Scaling m(B_{n,r}) = r^n m(B_{n,1}) — Lebesgue measure under dilation; (iii) DCT: pointwise a.e. convergence + integrable dominator implies integral convergence; (iv) Telescoping product: if ratios -> 0, the product decays super-exponentially. None references the others.\n\nLEAN STATUS: 8 lemmas closed (zero sorry): ballSlice definition, nonneg, le_one, lt_one, pow_tendsto (pointwise convergence), eq_zero_of_abs_gt_one, norm_ballSlice_pow_le (domination by indicator), indicator_Icc_integrable. 1 sorry remaining: the final DCT wiring (tendsto_integral_of_dominated_convergence). Blocker: AEStronglyMeasurable for (fun t => ballSlice t ^ n). ballSlice is piecewise-continuous (sqrt on measurableSet_Icc, 0 elsewhere), so it's Measurable, hence StronglyMeasurable, hence AEStronglyMeasurable. The Mathlib path would be Measurable.piecewise + measurable_sqrt + Measurable.pow. Once that's established, the three DCT hypotheses (pointwise a.e., domination, integrable bound) are all proved and the theorem closes."}, :classify {:classification :partial, :rationale "Informal proof complete for all 3 parts. Lean: 8/9 lemmas closed (zero sorry). One real partial: the DCT application is blocked on AEStronglyMeasurable for ballSlice^n. HtDP design sketch in the Lean file documents the exact composition path (Measurable.piecewise + measurable_sqrt + Measurable.pow -> AEStronglyMeasurable -> tendsto_integral_of_dominated_convergence).", :notes "CONFIDENCE INVERSION: The surprise is that high-dimensional balls have vanishing volume. The unit ball in R^n occupies fraction vol(B_n)/2^n of the unit cube, and this fraction goes to zero FASTER than any exponential. In R^100, the ball is roughly 10^{-40} of the cube. Your intuition that 'more dimensions = more room' is exactly wrong: more dimensions means more corners, and the ball misses all of them. This is the curse of dimensionality made precise, and it is why kNN and kernel density estimation fail in high dimensions."}, :integrate {:rationale "Three-part proof complete; Lean 8/9 closed.", :ledger-changes [], :notes "CONNECTIONS: (1) Concentration of measure: uniform distributions on high-dimensional balls concentrate on thin shells near the boundary. (2) Curse of dimensionality in ML: volume-based methods degrade because nearly all volume is in corners. (3) Stirling gives the same result via Gamma functions, but the slicing proof is more elegant and uses only measure-theory tools. (4) Gaussian annulus theorem: Gaussians in R^n concentrate at radius sqrt(n), the probabilistic cousin of this volume decay.\n\nEXAM-DAY FIELD KIT: (1) Cavalieri/Fubini slicing: vol(B_{n+1}) = integral of vol(slice at height t) dt. (2) Scaling: m(B_{n,r}) = r^n m(B_{n,1}). (3) f(t) = sqrt(1-t^2) gives [f(t)]^n -> 0 a.e. with dominator chi_{[-1,1]}. (4) DCT closes the integral convergence. (5) Telescoping: ratio -> 0 implies product decays super-exponentially."}, :commit {:saved? true}, :gate-review {:gates-passed true, :result-status :partial}}, :cycle/started-at "2026-03-29T21:17:47.597322247Z", :cycle/updated-at "2026-03-29T21:23:03.070042514Z", :cycle/result-status :partial}], :proof/ledger {"part-a" {:item/id "part-a", :item/label "(a) Show that $\\exists f:\\R\\rightarrow [0,1]$ such that\n$m\\{B_{n", :item/status :open, :item/depends-on #{}, :item/unlocks #{"part-b"}, :item/evidence-type :analytical}, "part-b" {:item/id "part-b", :item/label "(b) Show that $\\int[f(t)]^n dt\\rightarrow 0$ as $n\\rightarrow\n\\i", :item/status :open, :item/depends-on #{"part-a"}, :item/unlocks #{"part-c"}, :item/evidence-type :analytical}, "part-c" {:item/id "part-c", :item/label "(c) Show that for any finite positive number $A$, $A^n\nm\\{B_{n,1", :item/status :open, :item/depends-on #{"part-b"}, :item/unlocks #{"root"}, :item/evidence-type :analytical}, "root" {:item/id "root", :item/label "Complete proof of a01A04", :item/status :open, :item/depends-on #{"part-c"}, :item/unlocks #{}, :item/evidence-type :analytical}}, :proof/active-license nil, :proof/current-mode :CONSTRUCT, :proof/problem-id "apm-a01A04", :proof/canonical {:statement "Let $B_{m,1}$ denote the ball of radius $1$ centered at the origin in\n$\\Rm$.\n%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%\n\\begin{alist}\n%------------------------------------------------------------------*\n\\item Show that $\\exists f:\\R\\rightarrow [0,1]$ such that\n$m\\{B_{n+1,1}\\}=m\\{B_{n,1}\\}\\int [f(t)]^n dt$.\n%------------------------------------------------------------------*\n\\item Show that $\\int[f(t)]^n dt\\rightarrow 0$ as $n\\rightarrow\n\\infty$.\n%------------------------------------------------------------------*\n\\item Show that for any finite positive number $A$, $A^n\nm\\{B_{n,1}\\}\\rightarrow 0$ as $n\\rightarrow \\infty$.\n%------------------------------------------------------------------*\n\\end{alist}\n%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%\n\n", :closure-criterion "All parts proved analytically", :statement-hash "11ef1e2e616f19b77c4dfb3275f2d6069f8567605129da193832cd4dc7c0ffab", :version-history [{:version 0, :statement "Let $B_{m,1}$ denote the ball of radius $1$ centered at the origin in\n$\\Rm$.\n%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%\n\\begin{alist}\n%------------------------------------------------------------------*\n\\item Show that $\\exists f:\\R\\rightarrow [0,1]$ such that\n$m\\{B_{n+1,1}\\}=m\\{B_{n,1}\\}\\int [f(t)]^n dt$.\n%------------------------------------------------------------------*\n\\item Show that $\\int[f(t)]^n dt\\rightarrow 0$ as $n\\rightarrow\n\\infty$.\n%------------------------------------------------------------------*\n\\item Show that for any finite positive number $A$, $A^n\nm\\{B_{n,1}\\}\\rightarrow 0$ as $n\\rightarrow \\infty$.\n%------------------------------------------------------------------*\n\\end{alist}\n%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%\n\n", :hash "11ef1e2e616f19b77c4dfb3275f2d6069f856760